{{Expand German|Adelheid-Kreuz|date=August 2016}}
[[File:Adelheid-Kreuz.jpg|thumb|Cross of Adelheid]]
The '''Cross of Adelheid''' is an 11th and 12th century [[reliquary]] in the form of a [[crux gemmata]]. It is held in [[Saint Paul's Abbey, Lavanttal]]. It was commissioned by [[Adelaide of Rheinfelden|Adelheid]], daughter of [[Rudolf of Rheinfelden]], passing to [[St. Blaise Abbey, Black Forest|St. Blaise Abbey]] in the 19th century before coming to its present home. It is made of a wooden core covered with gilded silver plate. On the front are gems, pearls and precious stones. It is 82.9 cm high, 65.4 cm wide and 7.4 to 7.8 cm deep.

