'''Multi-functional Satellite Augmentation System''' ('''MTSAT''' or '''MSAS''')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/icg/2008/icg3/08-1.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-05-10 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106015542/http://www.unoosa.org/pdf/icg/2008/icg3/08-1.pdf |archivedate=2015-11-06 |df= }}</ref> is a [[Japan]]ese [[satellite based augmentation system]] (SBAS), i.e. a [[satellite navigation system]] which supports [[differential GPS]] (DGPS) to supplement the [[GPS]] system by reporting (then improving) on the reliability and accuracy of those signals. MSAS is operated by Japan's [[Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism|Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport]] [[Japan Civil Aviation Bureau]] (JCAB). Tests have been accomplished successfully, MSAS for aviation use was commissioned on 27 September 2007.
The use of SBASs, such as MSAS, enables an individual GPS receiver to correct its own position, offering a much greater accuracy. Typically GPS signal accuracy is improved from some 20 meters to approximately 1.5–2 meters in both the horizontal and vertical dimensions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gps.faa.gov/Library/waas-f-text.htm |title=Wide Area Augmentation System |archivedate=June 12, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612214444/http://gps.faa.gov/Library/waas-f-text.htm}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" ! Satellite Name & Details ! NMEA / PRN ! Location ! Launched |- |[http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraftDisplay.do?id=2005-006A MTSAT-1R] |NMEA #42 / PRN #129 |140°E | 26 February 2005 |- |[http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraftDisplay.do?id=2006-004A MTSAT-2] |NMEA #50 / PRN #137 |145°E | 18 February 2006 |}
MSAS provides a similar service to [[Wide Area Augmentation System]] (WAAS) in North America, and [[European Geostationary Navigation Overlay Service]] (EGNOS) in Europe.
